---
title: "Building LateralusOS"
author: bad-antics
date: 2026-04-06
abstract: We're making progress on LateralusOS, an operating system whose userspace is written in Lateralus. In this post, we'll discuss the kernel interface, init system, and what it means to dog-food your language at the OS layer.

## The Kernel Interface

We've made significant strides in establishing a stable kernel interface for LateralusOS. This involves defining a set of API calls that allow us to interact with the underlying hardware. Our initial implementation has focused on providing a subset of these APIs, which will serve as the foundation for our userspace.

fn kernel_init() -> bool {
    // Initialize hardware resources
    let resources = hardware_resources_init();
    
    // Set up kernel scheduler
    kernel_scheduler_setup(resources);
    
    return true;
}

## The Init System

Next, we need to develop an init system that can boot our kernel and load the necessary components. We're currently exploring several options, including a simple boot loader and a more complex init system that can manage dependencies between components.

fn init_system() -> () {
    // Load kernel image
    kernel_image_load();
    
    // Boot kernel
    kernel_boot();
    
    // Load libraries
    library_loader_init();
}

## Dog-Fooding Your Language at the OS Layer

One of the most interesting aspects of building LateralusOS is the opportunity to "dog-food" our own language at the OS layer. This means that we get to see firsthand how our language's design decisions impact its performance and usability in a real-world setting. By doing so, we'll be able to refine our language and make it better suited for operating systems.

fn os_language_test() -> () {
    // Run Lateralus compiler
    lateralus_compiler_run();
    
    // Measure compilation time
    let compilation_time = measure_compilation_time();
    
    // Print results
    print_results(compilation_time);
}

## Conclusion

We've made significant progress on LateralusOS, and we're excited to continue working on this project. By sharing our experiences and insights with the community, we hope to accelerate the development of other languages designed for operating systems.

